You guys are a great example of what the world should (and can) be like. <br><br>
Striving to understand sometimes involves letting down your guard, ie listening to the other guy and EVEN admitting when one has made a mistake. I also sense the forgiveness that is necessary in keeping the thread and discussion alive.<br><br>
&quot;Meeting halfway&quot; allows us to hold on to what we perceive as precious, but also demands of us the courage to let go of the frivolous things that we have stubbornly held on to for all these many years. Like our pride.<br><br>
Speaking as one who served in Vietnam, I will say that most of us - if not all - have felt unappreciated for the sacrifices we gave. But, I have never failed to realize that a much greater sacrifice was paid by those who never returned home, those who returned home permanently scarred in so many terrible ways, and perhaps most of all, the families.<br><br>
I was never wounded physically, yet I have constant intrusive thoughts. What to do? Write down these thoughts and turn them into an advantage.<br><br>
Many returning vets say that they left a great deal of themselves in that far away land. Me? I BROUGHT BACK much.<br>
And in my own small way, I intend to share what I brought home with those who may not have left most of their's behind.<br><br>
I remember a few times receiving a drinks of water from a buddy when my canteens were empty. And I recall just about falling out of a &quot;hump&quot; and having my friends strip my pack of extra weight and divide it among themselves. We can still do this. We can divide the weight that our less fortunate brothers carry.<br><br>
Don't get me wrong, there are many who carry the guilt and they never set foot in Vietnam! Give them a voice and try to understand them! As one of the contributors in this thread said recently: We are all brothers. <br><br>
I recall someone else, who walked this earth 2000 years ago, who admonishes us to also think along those lines.<br><br>

